The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Broadband launch today

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Maran: Connect all

 New Delhi, Jan. 13: Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd (BSNL) and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Ltd (MTNL) will launch the broadband services across the country from Friday.

 Broadband is an always-on network capable of providing interactive voice, data and video services over your telephone lines with a maximum speed of 256 kilo bits per second (Kbps). At this speed, a 500-page book can be downloaded in 2-3 minutes.

 Dayanidhi Maran, Union minister for communications and information technology, will launch the broadband services from Chennai. The services will also be started simultaneously from Delhi, Mumbai, Hyderabad, Bangalore and Calcutta through video conferencing.

 BSNL will provide the broadband services in 198 cities spread across 24 territorial telecom circles in the country progressively by the end of March 2005.

 In Delhi and Mumbai, the services would be provided by MTNL.

 The communication minister is bullish about the broadband services and has said it would take the country forward in the field of communication and infotainment.

 The broadband services will provide high-speed Internet connectivity for various applications like web-browsing and e-commerce. In addition, the broadband is pegged as a $25-billion industry with a potential to offer employment to 1.9 million people.

 The total investment required by the broadband industry by 2010 is pegged at $5.35 billion.

 The customer can avail multi-cast video services, video on demand, bandwidth on demand and other value-added services.

 The network for broadband services has been designed to offer video, voice and data services to customers.

 The broadband service is expected to give a fillip to the growth of the gross domestic product and enhance the quality of life through societal applications, including tele-education, tele-medicine, e-governance, entertainment as well as employment generation. 




